00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:03.443
So just some review
from last time--

00:02:03.443 --> 00:02:05.110
here's the Schrodinger
equation that I'm

00:02:05.110 --> 00:02:08.949
sure you're all sick
of seeing by now.

00:02:08.949 --> 00:02:12.280
In general, if our system
is time independent,

00:02:12.280 --> 00:02:14.950
then our Hamiltonian is
going to be time independent.

00:02:14.950 --> 00:02:17.020
And we can separate
the variables

00:02:17.020 --> 00:02:19.720
into the spatial component
and the time component.

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:22.180
And then by dividing
out the time component,

00:02:22.180 --> 00:02:24.610
we are left with this
stationary, time-independent

00:02:24.610 --> 00:02:26.232
Schrodinger equation.

00:02:26.232 --> 00:02:28.190
And that's the equation
that we've been solving

00:02:28.190 --> 00:02:29.950
and we will continue to solve.

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:39.320
So as I said, last time we
talked about the hydrogen atom.

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:42.050
We just solved its Hamiltonian.

00:02:42.050 --> 00:02:45.380
The Hamiltonian itself is,
of course, the kinetic energy

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:47.490
and the potential energy.

00:02:47.490 --> 00:02:49.790
The kinetic energy is this.

00:02:49.790 --> 00:02:52.940
The potential energy is actually
just that Coulomb attraction

00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:56.690
between the electron and the
proton in that hydrogen atom.

00:02:56.690 --> 00:03:01.490
And this, we saw, was
pretty simple to solve.

00:03:01.490 --> 00:03:04.340
I guess we didn't actually do
it, but the way this is solved

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:06.380
is you switch into
spherical coordinates.

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:10.730
You solve for a radial
component of the wave function,

00:03:10.730 --> 00:03:13.430
and an angular component
of the wave function.

00:03:13.430 --> 00:03:16.760
So to any of you who have
had a lot of chemistry,

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:18.990
these probably
look very familiar.

00:03:18.990 --> 00:03:28.390
So this is the s, these three
are p, these five are d.

00:03:28.390 --> 00:03:31.780
And these are basically
just the spherical harmonics

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:35.170
that you get from
solving the theta and phi

00:03:35.170 --> 00:03:39.000
parts of the Hamiltonian.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.540
And when we combine these,
we get the total spatial wave

00:03:44.540 --> 00:03:47.250
function for the hydrogen atom.

00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:51.440
So the spatial wave
function is described

00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:53.540
by these quantum numbers.

00:03:53.540 --> 00:03:57.710
And the principle quantum
number, l, the angular momentum

00:03:57.710 --> 00:04:01.370
component, and m l, which is
the angular momentum component,

00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:03.240
projected along the z axis.

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:06.910
So you guys have probably
seen these a million times--

00:04:06.910 --> 00:04:10.900
that leads to these
spatial wave functions.

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:13.780
So this is increasing
principal quantum number

00:04:13.780 --> 00:04:15.880
and this is increasing
angular momentum.

00:04:19.329 --> 00:04:21.579
All right, so we've all
seen this graph now a couple

00:04:21.579 --> 00:04:22.240
of times.

00:04:22.240 --> 00:04:27.502
Can somebody tell me what
this graph represents?

00:04:27.502 --> 00:04:35.185
